<section xml:id="section-assignment-week8">
  <title>Week 8 Assignment</title>
  <p><ol>
    <li>
      <p>
        Calculate the determinants of the following matrices.  Show
        the steps of the algorithm clearly or give a clear reason for
        the determinant using some other properties. (16). 
      </p>
      <p><ol>
        <li><me>
          \begin{pmatrix}
            3 \amp -2 \amp 1 \\
            -2 \amp 1 \amp 6 \\
            -1 \amp 1 \amp 7
          \end{pmatrix} 
        </me></li>
        <li><me>
          \begin{pmatrix}
            -4 \amp \frac{1}{2} \amp 3 \\
            \frac{1}{3} \amp \frac{-1}{3} \amp 6 \\
            2 \amp 0 \amp -7
          \end{pmatrix} 
        </me></li>
        <li><me>
          \begin{pmatrix}
            -7 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
            95 \amp \frac{1}{7} \amp 0 \\
            317 \amp -219 \amp 4 
          \end{pmatrix} 
        </me></li>
        <li><me>
          \begin{pmatrix}
            2 \amp 0 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp 2 \\
            0 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp 2 \amp 0 \\
            2 \amp 0 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp 2 \\
            0 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp 2 \amp 0 \\
            2 \amp 0 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp 2 
          \end{pmatrix} 
        </me></li>
      </ol></p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Under what conditions for <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are the
        following matrices invertible? (6) 
      </p>
      <p><ol>
        <li><me>
          \begin{pmatrix}
            a \amp 3 \amp 0 \\
            0 \amp b \amp 0 \\
            -1 \amp -1 \amp -1 
          \end{pmatrix} 
        </me></li>
        <li><me>
          \begin{pmatrix}
            a \amp 0 \amp a \\
            b \amp 0 \amp -b \\
            0 \amp 4 \amp 0 
          \end{pmatrix} 
        </me></li>
      </ol></p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Using the definition and properties of the determinant from
        the videos and the notes, prove the following statements. 
        Assume, throughout, that <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are
        <m>n \times n </m> matrices. (Some of these proofs are just
        one or two lines, connecting the relevant properties from
        different sections of the notes. Others are short calculations
        using the properties. Don't expect any of these to be long
        arguments. The long list of equivalent properties of
        invertible matrices will be useful.) (15)
      </p>
      <p><ol>
        <li>
          If <m>\Image A = \{0\}</m>, then <m>\det A = 0</m>.
        </li>
        <li>
          If <m>AA^TA</m> is invertible, then <m>A</m> is invertible.
        </li>
        <li>
          <m>ABA^{-1}</m> has the same rank as <m>B</m>, assuming that
          <m>A</m> is invertible. 
        </li>
        <li>
          If <m>A</m> is invertible, then the kernel of <m>A^{-1}</m>
          must be <m>\{0\}</m>. 
        </li>
        <li>
          There exist matrices <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> such that neither
          has kernel equal to <m>\RR^2</m>, but <m>\Ker (AB) =
          \RR^n</m>. 
        </li>
      </ol></p>
    </li>
  </ol></p>
</section>
